tweets.text: Black Sluice Lock in #Boston #Lincolnshire is open to allow water to travel out of the South Forty Foot to The Wash reducing flood risk. Our teams are out across the #Midlands checking on the rivers & water courses. Keep up to date with flood alerts here: https://t.co/RBrenwSYbD https://t.co/g8Irj3A1LE
Once the spillways stop running we can get pumping. While we have additional temporary pumps set up, we will start with our permanent pumping stations.

As expected the recent rain is passing through our river catchments. On the Somerset Levels and Moors the Hook Bridge spillway (River Tone) has been running but has now stopped, while Aller Moor spillway (River Parrett) continues to run.

Working together with partners is so important in #flood planning and we've been working together with @EnvAgencyMids on the #Ironbridge deployment of our @GeodesignB barrier since 2003! Yet again, they have done a brilliant job. #StormChristoph Thread! https://t.co/TufOonnNpm

3/3 Meantime we’ve worked with barrier supplier @GeodesignB on other changes. We’ve set the barrier up further back (see arrow) so it’s flatter. We’re using a larger membrane so there’s more weight pushing down on the rd & we’ve changed the way we go round the trees & benches. https://t.co/WQSR2H4okG
